---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Triangle Calculator | Find Area, Perimeter & Missing Sides",
  description: "Calculate triangle area, perimeter, and missing side lengths instantly. Discover the exact formulas you need to solve any geometry problem.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": []
    },
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": meta.title,
      "description": meta.description,
      "datePublished": meta.published
    }
  ]
};
---
<SiteLayout site="siliconbased" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/triangle-calculator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Triangle Calculator</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Find area, perimeter, and missing properties instantly.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="error-message" id="error-msg"></div>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem; text-align: center; color: var(--text-secondary);">Enter any 3 known values (including at least one side) to calculate the rest.</p>

      <div class="input-grid">
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="side-a">Side a</label>
          <input type="number" id="side-a" min="0" step="any" placeholder="e.g. 5">
        </div>
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="side-b">Side b</label>
          <input type="number" id="side-b" min="0" step="any" placeholder="e.g. 6">
        </div>
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="side-c">Side c</label>
          <input type="number" id="side-c" min="0" step="any" placeholder="e.g. 7">
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="input-grid">
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="angle-a">Angle A (&deg;)</label>
          <input type="number" id="angle-a" min="0" max="180" step="any" placeholder="Opposite to a">
        </div>
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="angle-b">Angle B (&deg;)</label>
          <input type="number" id="angle-b" min="0" max="180" step="any" placeholder="Opposite to b">
        </div>
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="angle-c">Angle C (&deg;)</label>
          <input type="number" id="angle-c" min="0" max="180" step="any" placeholder="Opposite to c">
        </div>
      </div>

      <div style="display: flex; gap: 1rem; justify-content: center; margin-top: 1rem;">
        <button id="clear-btn" style="background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color);">Clear All</button>
      </div>

      <div class="result-card" id="results" style="display: none;">
        <div class="result-value" id="res-area">0.00</div>
        <div style="color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 1rem;">Area</div>

        <div class="result-grid">
          <div class="result-item">
            <div class="result-item-label">Perimeter</div>
            <div class="result-item-value" id="res-perimeter">-</div>
          </div>
          <div class="result-item">
            <div class="result-item-label">Semi-perimeter</div>
            <div class="result-item-value" id="res-semiperimeter">-</div>
          </div>
          <div class="result-item">
            <div class="result-item-label">Type</div>
            <div class="result-item-value" id="res-type" style="font-size: 1rem;">-</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>How Does the Triangle Calculator Work?</h2>
      <p>Geometry often presents us with partial information. You might know two sides and an angle, or perhaps all three sides, but you need to determine the remaining properties like the area, perimeter, or missing angles. Our interactive <strong>triangle calculator</strong> is designed to solve any valid triangle based on the information you provide.</p>

      <p>Whether you're a student checking your math homework, a carpenter verifying dimensions, or an engineer calculating structural forces, this tool applies the fundamental laws of trigonometry instantly and accurately. We encourage you to also check out our <a href="/final-calculator" style="color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: underline;">final calculator</a> for managing your academic grades once your math homework is complete.</p>

      <h3>Core Triangle Properties</h3>
      <p>A standard triangle consists of three sides (labeled <em>a</em>, <em>b</em>, and <em>c</em>) and three interior angles (labeled <em>A</em>, <em>B</em>, and <em>C</em>). By convention, Angle A is opposite Side a, Angle B is opposite Side b, and Angle C is opposite Side c.</p>
      <p>To completely solve a triangle (find all its sides and angles), you need to know exactly three of its six properties, and at least one of those must be a side length. Knowing just three angles only gives you the shape (a family of similar triangles), not the specific size.</p>

      <h3>The Law of Sines</h3>
      <p>The Law of Sines is a powerful equation that establishes a proportional relationship between the sides of a triangle and the sines of their corresponding opposite angles. It is written as:</p>
      <div style="background: var(--bg-color); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; font-family: var(--font-mono); text-align: center; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
        a / sin(A) = b / sin(B) = c / sin(C)
      </div>
      <p>This formula is particularly useful in two scenarios:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>AAS or ASA:</strong> When you know two angles and one side.</li>
        <li><strong>SSA:</strong> When you know two sides and a non-included angle (though this can sometimes result in two valid triangles, known as the ambiguous case).</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>The Law of Cosines</h3>
      <p>The Law of Cosines is an extension of the Pythagorean theorem that applies to all triangles, not just right-angled ones. It relates all three sides to one angle. The formulas are:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>a&sup2; = b&sup2; + c&sup2; - 2bc &middot; cos(A)</li>
        <li>b&sup2; = a&sup2; + c&sup2; - 2ac &middot; cos(B)</li>
        <li>c&sup2; = a&sup2; + b&sup2; - 2ab &middot; cos(C)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>This law is essential when you have:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>SSS:</strong> All three sides are known, and you need to find the angles.</li>
        <li><strong>SAS:</strong> Two sides and the included angle are known, and you need to find the third side.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Calculating the Area</h3>
      <p>There are multiple ways to calculate the area of a triangle depending on what information is available. If you know the base and the height, the formula is simply <code>Area = 0.5 &times; base &times; height</code>.</p>
      <p>However, if you only know the three side lengths (a, b, c), the most efficient method is <strong>Heron's Formula</strong>. First, calculate the semi-perimeter (s):</p>
      <div style="background: var(--bg-color); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; font-family: var(--font-mono); text-align: center; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
        s = (a + b + c) / 2
      </div>
      <p>Then, plug it into the area formula:</p>
      <div style="background: var(--bg-color); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; font-family: var(--font-mono); text-align: center; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
        Area = &radic;(s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c))
      </div>
      <p>If you know two sides and the included angle (SAS), you can use the sine area formula: <code>Area = 0.5 &times; a &times; b &times; sin(C)</code>.</p>

      <h3>Validating a Triangle</h3>
      <p>Not every combination of numbers can form a valid triangle. The <strong>Triangle Inequality Theorem</strong> states that the sum of the lengths of any two sides must be strictly greater than the length of the remaining third side. If <code>a + b &le; c</code>, the triangle cannot physically exist.</p>
      <p>Additionally, the sum of all three interior angles in any planar triangle must always equal exactly 180 degrees (or &pi; radians). If the provided angles add up to more or less than 180&deg;, the inputs are invalid.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Why can't I solve a triangle with just three angles (AAA)?</summary>
        <p>Knowing only the three interior angles defines the shape of the triangle but not its size. There are infinitely many similar triangles that share the same three angles but have different side lengths. To determine the exact dimensions, you must know at least one side length to anchor the scale.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the ambiguous case of the Law of Sines?</summary>
        <p>The ambiguous case occurs when you are given two sides and a non-included angle (SSA). Depending on the specific measurements, this information might describe no valid triangle, exactly one valid triangle, or two completely different valid triangles. This happens because the sine function is positive for both acute and obtuse angles.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does the calculator handle right-angled triangles?</summary>
        <p>A right-angled triangle is simply a specific case where one of the angles is exactly 90 degrees. Our calculator automatically applies the general Law of Sines and Law of Cosines, which seamlessly handle 90-degree angles just like any other value. If you input properties that define a right triangle, it will calculate it perfectly.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is Heron's formula?</summary>
        <p>Heron's formula is a mathematical method for calculating the area of a triangle when only the lengths of all three sides are known. You do not need to know any angles or heights. You first find the semi-perimeter (half the perimeter), and then calculate the square root of the product of the semi-perimeter and its differences with each of the three sides.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why do I get an "Invalid Triangle" error?</summary>
        <p>This error appears when the inputs violate the fundamental laws of geometry. The most common reasons are: the sum of the angles provided is greater than 180 degrees, or the side lengths violate the Triangle Inequality Theorem (where the sum of any two sides must be greater than the third side).</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const inputs = {
        a: document.getElementById('side-a'),
        b: document.getElementById('side-b'),
        c: document.getElementById('side-c'),
        A: document.getElementById('angle-a'),
        B: document.getElementById('angle-b'),
        C: document.getElementById('angle-c')
      };

      const errorMsg = document.getElementById('error-msg');
      const resultsDiv = document.getElementById('results');
      const clearBtn = document.getElementById('clear-btn');

      const resArea = document.getElementById('res-area');
      const resPerimeter = document.getElementById('res-perimeter');
      const resSemiperimeter = document.getElementById('res-semiperimeter');
      const resType = document.getElementById('res-type');

      const toRad = deg => deg * (Math.PI / 180);
      const toDeg = rad => rad * (180 / Math.PI);

      // Helper to format numbers cleanly
      const fmt = (num) => {
        if (num === null || isNaN(num)) return '';
        return Number.isInteger(num) ? num.toString() : parseFloat(num.toFixed(4)).toString();
      };

      function getValues() {
        const vals = {};
        for (const [key, el] of Object.entries(inputs)) {
          const val = parseFloat(el.value);
          vals[key] = isNaN(val) || val <= 0 ? null : val;
        }
        return vals;
      }

      function showError(msg) {
        errorMsg.textContent = msg;
        errorMsg.style.display = 'block';
        resultsDiv.style.display = 'none';
      }

      function clearError() {
        errorMsg.style.display = 'none';
        errorMsg.textContent = '';
      }

      function solveSSS(a, b, c) {
        if (a + b <= c || a + c <= b || b + c <= a) return { error: "Invalid side lengths. The sum of any two sides must be greater than the third." };
        const A = toDeg(Math.acos((b*b + c*c - a*a) / (2*b*c)));
        const B = toDeg(Math.acos((a*a + c*c - b*b) / (2*a*c)));
        const C = 180 - A - B;
        return { a, b, c, A, B, C };
      }

      function solveSAS(a, C, b) {
        const c = Math.sqrt(a*a + b*b - 2*a*b*Math.cos(toRad(C)));
        return solveSSS(a, b, c);
      }

      function solveASA(A, c, B) {
        const C = 180 - A - B;
        if (C <= 0) return { error: "Angles sum to 180 or more." };
        const a = (c * Math.sin(toRad(A))) / Math.sin(toRad(C));
        const b = (c * Math.sin(toRad(B))) / Math.sin(toRad(C));
        return { a, b, c, A, B, C };
      }

      function solveAAS(A, B, a) {
        const C = 180 - A - B;
        if (C <= 0) return { error: "Angles sum to 180 or more." };
        const c = (a * Math.sin(toRad(C))) / Math.sin(toRad(A));
        const b = (a * Math.sin(toRad(B))) / Math.sin(toRad(A));
        return { a, b, c, A, B, C };
      }

      function solveSSA(a, b, A) {
        // Find B using Law of Sines: sin(B) = (b * sin(A)) / a
        const sinB = (b * Math.sin(toRad(A))) / a;
        if (sinB > 1) return { error: "No possible triangle matches these values." };

        // For simplicity in this calculator, we only return the primary acute angle triangle
        // The ambiguous case could yield a second obtuse triangle, but we keep it basic
        const B = toDeg(Math.asin(sinB));
        const C = 180 - A - B;
        if (C <= 0) return { error: "Invalid angle combination resulting from SSA." };
        const c = Math.sqrt(a*a + b*b - 2*a*b*Math.cos(toRad(C)));
        return { a, b, c, A, B, C };
      }

      function determineTriangleType(a, b, c, A, B, C) {
        let sideType = "Scalene";
        // allow minor float tolerance
        const eps = 0.001;
        if (Math.abs(a - b) < eps && Math.abs(b - c) < eps) sideType = "Equilateral";
        else if (Math.abs(a - b) < eps || Math.abs(b - c) < eps || Math.abs(a - c) < eps) sideType = "Isosceles";

        let angleType = "Acute";
        if (Math.abs(A - 90) < eps || Math.abs(B - 90) < eps || Math.abs(C - 90) < eps) angleType = "Right";
        else if (A > 90 || B > 90 || C > 90) angleType = "Obtuse";

        return `${angleType} ${sideType}`;
      }

      function calculate() {
        const v = getValues();
        let solved = null;
        clearError();

        let knownSides = (v.a ? 1 : 0) + (v.b ? 1 : 0) + (v.c ? 1 : 0);
        let knownAngles = (v.A ? 1 : 0) + (v.B ? 1 : 0) + (v.C ? 1 : 0);
        let totalKnown = knownSides + knownAngles;

        // Validation rules
        if (v.A !== null && v.B !== null && v.C !== null) {
          const sum = v.A + v.B + v.C;
          if (Math.abs(sum - 180) > 0.1) {
            showError("The three angles must sum to exactly 180°.");
            return;
          }
        }

        if (totalKnown < 3) {
          resultsDiv.style.display = 'none';
          return;
        }
        if (knownSides === 0) {
          showError("At least one side length must be provided.");
          return;
        }

        // Identify the case and solve
        if (v.a && v.b && v.c) {
          solved = solveSSS(v.a, v.b, v.c);
        } else if (knownSides === 2 && knownAngles === 1) {
          if (v.a && v.b && v.C) solved = solveSAS(v.a, v.C, v.b);
          else if (v.b && v.c && v.A) solved = solveSAS(v.b, v.A, v.c);
          else if (v.a && v.c && v.B) solved = solveSAS(v.a, v.B, v.c);
          else if (v.a && v.b && v.A) solved = solveSSA(v.a, v.b, v.A);
          else if (v.a && v.b && v.B) solved = solveSSA(v.b, v.a, v.B);
          else if (v.b && v.c && v.B) solved = solveSSA(v.b, v.c, v.B);
          else if (v.b && v.c && v.C) solved = solveSSA(v.c, v.b, v.C);
          else if (v.a && v.c && v.C) solved = solveSSA(v.c, v.a, v.C);
          else if (v.a && v.c && v.A) solved = solveSSA(v.a, v.c, v.A);
        } else if (knownSides === 1 && knownAngles >= 2) {
          // If two angles are known, find the third
          let A = v.A, B = v.B, C = v.C;
          if (A && B && !C) C = 180 - A - B;
          else if (B && C && !A) A = 180 - B - C;
          else if (A && C && !B) B = 180 - A - C;

          if (A + B + C > 180.1) {
            showError("Sum of angles exceeds 180°.");
            return;
          }

          if (v.c) solved = solveASA(A, v.c, B);
          else if (v.a) solved = solveASA(B, v.a, C); // map differently
          else if (v.b) solved = solveASA(C, v.b, A);
        }

        if (!solved) {
          showError("Not enough compatible info provided.");
          return;
        }

        if (solved.error) {
          showError(solved.error);
          return;
        }

        // Update input fields with calculated values
        if (!v.a) inputs.a.value = fmt(solved.a);
        if (!v.b) inputs.b.value = fmt(solved.b);
        if (!v.c) inputs.c.value = fmt(solved.c);
        if (!v.A) inputs.A.value = fmt(solved.A);
        if (!v.B) inputs.B.value = fmt(solved.B);
        if (!v.C) inputs.C.value = fmt(solved.C);

        // Calculate results
        const perim = solved.a + solved.b + solved.c;
        const semi = perim / 2;
        // Heron's formula
        let area = Math.sqrt(Math.max(0, semi * (semi - solved.a) * (semi - solved.b) * (semi - solved.c)));

        resArea.textContent = fmt(area);
        resPerimeter.textContent = fmt(perim);
        resSemiperimeter.textContent = fmt(semi);
        resType.textContent = determineTriangleType(solved.a, solved.b, solved.c, solved.A, solved.B, solved.C);

        resultsDiv.style.display = 'block';
      }

      for (const el of Object.values(inputs)) {
        el.addEventListener('input', () => {
          // When a user types, we should maybe allow them to edit freely.
          // Real-time calculation can be tricky if they clear a field.
          calculate();
        });
      }

      clearBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        for (const el of Object.values(inputs)) el.value = '';
        clearError();
        resultsDiv.style.display = 'none';
      });

    });
  </script>
  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .calculator-container { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
    .input-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(150px, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .input-group { margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .input-group label { display: block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-primary); }
    input, select { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; font-size: 1rem; }
    input:focus, select:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 20%, transparent); }
    button { background: var(--accent-color); color: white; border: none; padding: 0.75rem 2rem; border-radius: 8px; font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; font-size: 1rem; }
    button:hover { opacity: 0.9; }
    .result-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); border: 1px solid var(--accent-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; text-align: center; }
    .result-value { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .result-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(120px, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; margin-top: 1.5rem; }
    .result-item { background: var(--bg-color); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 8px; padding: 1rem; text-align: center; }
    .result-item-label { font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 0.25rem; }
    .result-item-value { font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .error-message { color: #ef4444; background: rgba(239, 68, 68, 0.1); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; margin-bottom: 1rem; display: none; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }
    .explainer { margin-top: 3rem; }
    .explainer h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .explainer h3 { font-size: 1.4rem; margin: 2rem 0 1rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .explainer p { margin-bottom: 1.25rem; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .explainer ul { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .explainer li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
